{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_eustachy_ver01/data/sn83030214/00206532579/1920112501/0706.xml":{"full_text":"Sm? Han* S?riinitu\nFirrt to Last?the Truth: News?Edi?\ntorials?Advertisements\nMH? ?f the Audit Bureau of Circulation*\nTHURSDAY. NOVEMBER 25, 1920\nOwn*? and published dally bjr Now Turk Tribune\nIm.. N?s? York Corporation. OltdiHI Held. I'rnri\n?lent; O. Venior l'ogors. Vie*. President; Helen\nlitwen Held, Secretary; It K. Msiflo'.it. Treasurer.\n.Address. Tribun? Butldini. IS! Nassau Street, New\n\\orfc Telephone, Beekman \"000.\nSUBSCRIPTION- RATES -By ma'.!. Including\nI'ostaie. IN THE 1 -MTK7I STATES.\nOu? Six One\nTiy Mill Poatpa'.d. Tear. Month? Month.\nI'ally and P'indav.$17!.0? $6.Oil $100\num week. roc.\nSunday only. 4.00 SS .40\nSunday only, Canada. 6 00 .53\nFOREIGN RATES\n?illy er.d Sunday.$28.00 $13 ro $.'40\n\"ally only. 1?-40 8 70 147.\nSunday only. 9 7', 5.13 .86\nBntared at tha Posto?? at New York as Second\nClass Mall Matter\nY#u can purchase merchandise advertised In THF\nTRIBUNE with -absolute ?aferv?.tor it dissatisfac?\ntion rtaults In any case THE TRIBUNE ouarantres\npay your money bark upon request. No red tape.\nNo ?ulbblln?. We make oood promptly If the\n???rtUer does not.\nMEMBER OR. TIT17 ASSOCIATED press\nTh? Associsted Press Is exclusively entitled to the\nrae for republlcatlon of all new? dispatches\n?rodlted to It or not otherwise credited in tiil< paper,\nand also the local news of spontaneous origin pub?\nlished herein.\nAll rights of republlcatlon of all other matter\nher<Hn also are reserved.\nA Day of Promise\nNot so much for blessings in hand\nas for the assurance cf better things\nto come is this year's Thanksgiving\nDay marked. America and the\nworld are still in the backwash of\nthe war. Nations are but just\nlearning the worst about much that\nappened in those years of stress.\nReadjustment is still the compelling\niorce, in industry, in politics, in\nmorals. Violent crime is still ram?\npant. Bolshevism clings to the sad?\ndle in Russia. Rumblings of unrest\nrecur in many quarters.\nBut the broad gains of the year\niar outweigh the losses, and the basis\nfor future gains is broad and sound.\nBolshevism may last many months\nas a local military despotism; as an\nidea, with potency to undermine gov?\nernments and economic systems, it\nhas lost every vestige of threat. It\nftands so discredited to-day among\nall classes everywhere that its in?\nfluence is wholly salutary, a wreck?\nage to warn other vessels from a\ntreacherous shore. Unless all sur?\nface signs belie the depths, 1920 is\nto mark not only the crest of radical?\nism but its swift recession, a wave\nbroken to harmlessness upon inevi?\ntable facts.\nHere in America the processes of\nadjustment are proceeding normally,\nas rapidly as safety will permit, and\nwith every promise of.clear and set?\ntled weather in the not distant fu?\nture. One hundred more days of\nthe Tumulty regime remain. They\ncan be passed over cheerfully and\ngood-naturedly in view of the four\nyears of order and reason that are\nscheduled to succeed them. An able\nand thorough job was performed by\nthe American voters on Election\nPay. They can well be thankful for\nthe blessings thereby earned, even\nthough not immediately to be en?\njoyed.\nPatience is still needed. Rest and\na careful invalidism after a series of\nmajor operations are still needed by\nthe shell-scarred old world. But\nthere is ample ground for devout\nthanksgiving, in that recuperation\nhas proceeded as rapidly as it has\nend that complete restoration is no\nremote dream. At least it seems\nsafe to assert that the patient is out\nof danger.\nBolshevik Patriotism\nTo the confirmed Red patriotism\nis anathema. The new dispensation\nscorns loyalty to one's native land,\nrace and mother tongue. Such is\neither a superstition or a devilish\ntrick to keep the exploited masses in\nwilling subjection. Nationalism is\nhumbug, says the Marxist, and when\na bourgeois says he loves his country\nhe merely means he loves his class\nand the arrangement safeguarding\nits weajth and power.\nNow comes Karl Radek, the super\nBolshevik, and throws off the inter?\nnationalist mask. Writing in Frei?\nheit about the Russo-Polish war\nRadek maintains that the attitude of\nthe Russian Communists toward i\nRussia of which they form the gov\n*rning class ought to be radically\ndifferent from their attitude towarc\nthe old Russian state. Toward th<\nRussia of the czars the Communist!\nwere anti-patriots because the stat<\nwas their enemy; but. toward th?\nRussia of the Soviets they must b?\npatriots because the new Russii\nmeans themselves.\nThis argument puts into a glar\niug ligh\"; the intellectual dishonest;\nof the Bolshevik!, who pretend t\ndespise in their opponents the sam\nquality which they extol in their\nh. selves. If L?nine and Trotzky may ar.\npeal to the patriotism of Russians i\nIt is sheer hypocrisy to pretend abroa\nthat the Bolshevik is an internatior\nalist. The hypocrisy ij, similar t\nthat of the German militarists wh\nused to preach pacifism in and fo\nEngland, France and America whil\nwhetting their own weapons.\nThe fact is, of course, that th\nRussian patriotism of the Rade\nvariety? is not patriotism at all bu\nmere patrioteeritfg. It would e>\nploit for selfish, personal purpose\nthe patriotic sentiment in otheri\nRadek and his sort are out fo\npower, to feed their own vanity, ar\ncontrolled by motives of individua\naggrandizement. Such men are no\nunusual. History records the i\nmaleficent influence. Pretended pa\ntrlotism at home and Marxisn\nabroad, one or the other is empha?\nsized in accord as to which course is\nthe more likely to bring personal\npower.\nVon Rintelen'8 Release\nPresident Wilson's commutation of\nthe sentence imposed on Franz von,\nRintelen, a former officer of the Ger?\nman army, who w'as sent to this\ncountry when it was at ?peace to\nurge treacherous war on us, raises\nan interesting question.\nVon Rintelen was tried three\ntimes and three times convicted.\nFirst, for having conspired to sup?\npress legal American trade; second,\nfor fraudulently obtaining a pass?\nport; third, for conspiring to de?\nstroy ships going from our ports to\nthose of the Allies by putting fire\nbombs in their cargoes. There were\nother even more heinous acts con?\nnected with the activities of Von\nRintelen, but the foregoing were the\n1 orinal accusations. Of his guilt\nthere was no pretense of doubt.\nWhat, then, was Von Rintelen?\nIv is not straining the facts to say\nthat he was a plotter of wholesale\ndestruction. He was the willing agent\nof those in Berlin who openly scoffed\nnot only at international law but all\nlaw. He was in the category of a\npirate. He was a guerrilla who\nsought to butcher the citizens of\nanother land with which his country\nwas at peace.\nAnd the President sees fit to re?\nlease him on the bare condition that\nhe shall leave the Unitee. States and\ngive a meagre $5,000 bond not to\ncome back!\nThe idea once prevailed that the\ninterests of civilization require that\nmen who become, scientific outlaws\nshould be punished in such manner\nas to deter others from displaying\nsimilar barbarism in the future. This\nidea would seem to be abandoned.\nIn its stead it is apparently assumed\nit Washington that such a criminal\nas Von Rintelen, now that the war is\nover, is entitled to amnesty as a\nmere political offender.\nThis is not merely condonation of\npersonal offenses, but a practical ac?\nknowledgment of the validity of the\nGerman claim that war releases the\ncitizens of a country at war from all\nmoral obligations. No comment on\nthe fundamental surrender such an\nacknowledgment implies seems nec?\nessary.\nMr. Coolidge Sums Up\n\"I doubt,\" says Governor Coolidge,\n\"if any particular mandate was\ngiven at the last election on the ques?\ntion of the League of Nations.\"\nThe Vice-President-elect speaks\ncandidly and sensibly, according to\nhis practice. No clean-cut and de?\nfined issue was submitted. Mr. Cox\ndanced about from one position to\nanother. Senator Harding-was de?\nliberately non-committal with respect\nto a precise program. He openly\navowed that he matured no policy.\nUnder the circumstances no popular\nmandate was possible.\nBut as to the objective, the policy\nto be adopted by Senator Harding\nwas explicit. 'The end was not na?\ntional aloofness, but participation in\nthe councils of mankind for the safe,\nguarding of peace. So the Chicago\nplatform declared. So the candidate\nrepeatedly asserted.\nThe Wilson league?that is, tin\nleague of which Article X was tin\nheart?is \"dead.\" But the broadei\nobligation to substitute something\nbetter for it persists. Senator Har\nding has recently moved in the direc\ntion of redeeming his pledge by call\ning a conference, just as he said h\nwould do.\nWhat Is Vanderlip?\nWhatever may be true concerr\ning one Washington D. Vanderlij\nwhose mfme is widely appearing i\nthe press, he is obviously a man n?7\nunmindful of the value of publicit;\nHe recalls Colonel Mulberry Sellei\nin his most imaginative mood an\nJ. Rufus Wallingford.\nGeneral knowledge of him beg;i\nwith the announcement from Mo\ncow that Mr. Vanderlip, a leadii\nAmerican banker and head of\npowerful financial syndicate, hi\nsecured from the Soviet gover\ni ment a concession to exploit son\nI 400,000 square miles of caste\nSiberia. 11. G. Wells, in one of 1\narticles on Russia, told of meetii\n.Mr. Vanderlip and gives the impri\nI sion that he understood he was t\nwell known international banker\nthe same name. L?nine had deem\nhis visitor of such importance th\nbe had paraded the Red army befo\n1 l.im, had made him economic ki\nof a vast region, and as part of t\nI deal had agreed to buy $3,000,00\nI 000 of American goods. In all\ni spects the story was such as to m<i\nthe other Mr. Vanderlip take do1\nand reread Edward Everett Hal\ntale, \"My Double and How He I\ndid Me.\"\nThe Moscow Vanderlip then\nturned home. There was such\nperson. He quickly formed eont;\nv. ith the newspapers, confirmed 1\nstory of his Golconda contract, a\nt-pread the idea that about all bu\nress men needed to do to get\nshare of the Russian loot was\nsend on their goods in his care.\nIn view of all this The Wee!\nReview has been led to investig;\nwho is Vanderlip. It reports tl\ntwenty years ago, when the Alas\ngold excitement was at its heig\nthe then Russian government gra\ned to one Vondaslarsky a six\nyear concession covering Ka\nchatka and northeastern Siberia\nElaborate explorations were made\non the theory that the same gold\ndeposits might extend to the ertst*\nern shore of Bering Sea. But\nnothing but an icy waste was found,\n7?f about the value of northern\nGreenland, and the concession has\nsince been dormant. Meanwhile a\nroving American prospector visited\nche region and brought back a\ncollection of Eskimo pictures with\nwhich he illustrated magazine\nstories of his adyentures. This\nprospector, it is said, bore the name\nof Washington D. Vanderlip.\nNothing yet has been done to jus?\ntify the issuance of a fraud order\nby the Postoffice Department, but\nthere is enough known to make fur?\nther investigation desirable before\ninvesting. Perhaps there are\ntreasures in eastern Siberia to be\nnad for the picking up, but perhaps\nthere are not. Perhaps, out of the\nloot of Russia L?nine has accumu?\nlated three billion and would be\nglad to use America as a \"fence,'\nbut perhaps he has not.\nBut, whatever the facts, it may be\npredicted that the Bolshevist\nminded will exploit the Vanderlij\nstory with energy and do what the>\ncan to promote the idea that we\nneed only to recognize L?nine tc\nget vast money gains. And, o1\ncourse, those who like to be fooler\nwill be fooled.\nNaval Essentials\nIn his address to the graduating\nclass at the Naval War College Ad?\nmiral Sims named four essential ele?\nments without which a navy cannot\nbe efficient for war:\n1. A fleet of adequate strength in\neach type of vessel.\n2. A thoroughly trained personnel\nto man this fleet.\n3. Thoroughly digested plans.\n4. A logical organization of the\nNavy Department.\nThe recent investigation of the\nconduct of the war demonstrated\nthat all four of these essentials were\nlacking when we declared war. What\nthe navy did it did in spite of its\nhandicaps?in spite of the disregard\nof Washington's wise admonition:\n1. We should be prepared.\n2. We should lie trained*^\n3. We should have a plan.\nAdmiral Sims adds a fourth essen?\ntial to the Washington list?.-namely,\na logical organization of the Navy\nDepartment. Without this a navy j\nefficient in itself may not be prop-\nerly employed?it might be defeated\nin war. The civil power, being\nsupreme, must function properly?\notherwise there may be failure.\nThe testimony before the Senate\nwas overwhelming in its condemna?\ntion of the present organization. Ad?\nmiral Benson and other apologists\nfor the Secretary were unanimous in\nfavor of reorganization. Captain\nPratt, the assistant chief of opera- j\ntions, states that from his experience\nin Mr. Daniels's office he would feel\ncompelled to decline the appointment\nas chief of operations under similar\nconditions in the event of future war.\nSophistry, the hysterical cry of\n\"Prussianism\" and other devices of\nMr. Daniels cannot prevent a proper\norganization of the Navy Depart?\nment under the next Administration.\nNear the Turn\nMr. Wilson vetoed the budget act\nbecause two of the officials created\nby it were made removable by Con?\ngress instead of by the President.\nIt was a minute fault, which could\nhave been cured, if necessary, at\nthis session.\nBut Congress will not make an\nissue with,the White House on this\nunimportant detail. The House al?\ntered the bill last summer to meet\nthe President's objections. The Sen?\nate will undoubtedly concur when it\nhas a chance to. Chairman. Good\ncontends Congress ought to have the\npower to discharge the budget di?\nrector and assistant director, but is\nwilling to wait until Mr. Wilson's\nterm ends before establishing the\npower.\nWhat is more important is to get\nthe new system working early next\nspring. The Harding Administra?\ntion will aim at economy. Hundreds\nof millions can be saved by control?\nling estimates at their sources and\nby eliminating duplication of gov?\nernmental agencies. Another leak\ncan bo stopped by restraining de?\npartment and bureau chiefs from\nrunning up deficits. For some years\npast these care-free spenders have\nlaughed at Congressional restric?\ntions on their financial operations.\nThey have overdrawn their accounts j\nand then called on Congress to\nsquare them with the Treasury.\nWith a real budget system this de?\nmoralizing practice will cease. The\npresent Administration was unwill-\ning to be hampered by accounting\nmethods. The new one will be of\ndifferent mind. The new system j\nwill be backed by a new spirit, and\nthe principle of scientific control j\nof expenditure will at last have a\ngenuine test.\nGenerous Grover Whalen\nGrover Whalen, editor of that in?\nteresting tabloid publication, The\nBuzz of the Busy Bus, and coinci\ndentally Commissioner of Plant and\nStructures, and as such grand pan?\njandrum of the Hylan transporta?\ntion system which was to tear the\nteeth from the mouth of greedy\nmonopoly, reveals himself as a man\nof the most generous nature.\nTestifying before the Lockwood\ncommittee, Mr. Whalen told the story\nof his inheritance. His father,\nnearly twenty years ago, left to him\nhis interest in the firm.of Holland\nCo., which owned valuable trucking\nequipment and had city street-cletin\ning contracts and other business\nconnections. Five months before he\nbecame the Mayor's private secre?\ntary and confidential adviser Mr.\nWhalen was moved to give to his\npartner, without money or price,\nevery dollar of his interest. Not a\npenny came to him. He asked no\naccounting. There was no writing\nto show the transfer. It would seem\nthat he merely called in his partner\nand said to him: \"Dear friend, it's\nyours, all yours.\"\nSubsequently, when this partner\nbegan to use the courthouse excava?\ntion as a dump, and so effectively\nfilled up the hole that it will cost the\ncity, if Mr. Untermyer is to be be?\nlieved, a half million to dig the stuff\nout, Mr. Whalen noted what was be?\ning done, but he regarded the. dump?\ning as a good thing. What is a hole\nfor if it is not a place to pmpty\nashes, tin cans and the like?\nIt is perhaps just as well that the\nHyian bus system was not further\ndevejoped. With Mr. Whalen in\ncharge, passionately devoted to giv?\ning property away, he might, in a\nburst of generosity, have thrust title\nto all the equipment and machinery\ninto the hands of some chance passer?\nby. Of wonderful quality are the\nagents selected by Mayor Hylan to\nachieve his great purpose of serving\nthe people!\nThe Real Ireland\nIts Loyally and Gallantry Contrasted\nWith Sinn Feiners\nTo the Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: With reference to a letter in\nyour columns of to-day, signed \"A\nConstant Reader,\" attempting to white?\nwash the Sinn Fein in Ireland, may I\ncall attention to the fact that the\nwriter is arguing on fallacious ground\nin several instance*?\n1. Sinn F?in and Ireland are not\nsynonymous by any means. The real\nIrish have been among the best de?\nfenders and greatest developers in trie\nBritish Empire. They are rnirt of the\nbackbone of every dominion and col?\nony, and they have fought for Lhat\nempire they helped to build in every\nwar. Every one honors the Dublin\nFusileers and other gallant Irish regi?\nments who gave their all for the\nempire. But let us not insult these\ngallant Irish, living and dead, by\nidentifying them with Sinn F?in, the\n\"Irish Bolshevists.\" Sinn F?in cannot\nbe credited in any way for the heroic\nactions of their compatriots who really\nserve Ireland.\n2. There is a disposition in America\nto credit Sinn F?in with the acts of\ngood Irish citizens h?7-re. The 69th\nRegiment is often alluded to in this\nconnection. The Irish here have noth?\ning to do with the Sinn F?in, and be?\ncause many of them have been good\ncitizens and gallant soldiers in Amer?\nica is not a point in favor of Sinn\nF?inism by any means. The thinking\nIrish in America naturally deplore the\nmurders now going on in 1 rehuid--and\nso do Englishmen- but they feel that\nAmerica must not interfere in a\nquestion which in no way concerns her.\n3. Home Tlule is passed. When file\nmurder gangs are wiped out Ireland,\nwith the same rule as Canada. Aus?\ntralia, New Zealand and South Africa,\nwill return to prosperity and will hold\nup lier head as a real shareholder in\nthe destiny of the great empire her\nsons have helped to build. Russia\ncannot live while Bolshevism rules;\nIreland cannot live until the blight of\nSinn F?inism is forever driven from\nthe island.\nWith \"A Constant Reader.\" I pity\nthe real Ireland and feel that we\nshould hell), ?f possible, by editorial\ncounsel. But to help the rea'. Ireland\nwe must awaken her to the full realiza?\ntion of the scourge of Sinn F?inism\nwhich threatens her very life.\nWILLIAM NEWMAN CHEW.\nBrooklyn, Nov. 1920.\nGreece Needs Monarchy\nTo the Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: In t>i<? columns of your paper, and,\nindeed, in those of most, of the great\njournals, I have noticed a tendency to\ni runt the result of the recent election in\nGreece us something of a misfortune to\nthat country and the world at, large.\nThis. I think, is a mistaken point of\nview. To iriy mind it represents the\nhealthful reaction from radicalism\nwhich is taking place.\nNo on?> could regard King Konstantine\nas an ideal monarch Nevertheless he\nis the rightful King of Greece, and his\ntriumph is not so much personal as the\ntriumph of a great principle. Tbe\nmonarchical principle had carried civil?\nization through many trying epochs. It\nhas stood for peace and order In a world\nof chaos. Even to-day in the most en?\nlightened countries democracy leaves\nmuch to be desired, and In those half\nformed nations of the Balkan peninsula\nit is1 as much out of place as it would\nbe in the nursery. They reach for it\nmerely because it is the fashion of th?\nhour.\nThe most hopeful sign that the peo?\nple of Greece may be trusted to take t\npart in governing themselves lies ir\ntheir decision to.recall their prdper gov\nernor. ALDEN H. HATCH.\nWoodmere, L. I.. Nov. 22, 1U20.\nA General Condition\ni From The Philadelphia Inquirer)\nTo the unprejudiced mind that has\nbeen following naval affairs for >,ome\ntime past the statement that \"academy\nmorale\" at Annapolis is at a low ebb\nwill not be surprising. As a matter\nof fact the morale of the whole navy\nseems way below par, a condition that\nis entirely consistent \\vi*h its manage?\nment by a fatuous, blundering and en?\ntirely self-satisfied country editor who\ndoesn't know a binnaclt* from a barna?\ncle, and who doesn't possess even the\nsaving grace of ordinary common sense.\nTheConning Tower\nTo Mies Lotus Robb\nf. Lotus Itohb, the April charm\nof whose delicate performance Deemed in\nthe confusion of lnst evening a thing\nwhich only lyric verse could adequately\ndescribe.?Alexander Woollcott in The\nTimes.]\nHad we the pen of a Woollcott,\nHad we the brain of a Broun,\nHad we a turn for melodies, like Kern,\nWere we a Herbert for tune;\nHad we the gift of a Gilbert,\nHad we the knack that is his,\nHaply you'd vote us r wonder, but,\nLotus,\nAin't this pretty good as it is?\nPleasant is the cairn that pervades\na newspaper office on a legal holiday.\nThe ticker is mute, except for a few\nfootball games; the trucks in Frank?\nfort Street, with their noisy horns and\nnoisier drivers, have a day off; no?\nbody calls because it is generally sup?\nposed that morning newspapers are\nnot published on the day following a\n?holiday; nothing is heard but the\nclicks of the typewriters and the tele?\ngraph machines. Let us give thanks.\nDear! dear! perhaps somebody will\ntry to prove that we have been selling\nthe contents of our zinc waste reposi?\ntory?selling them to a paper or a\nlin-on concern. It would amount up, in\nthe course of a decade.\nThe revenue on manuscripts telling\na \"story\" using all the names of the\ncurrent shows would be a tidy sum\nin itself.\nMAIN STREETS\nMost of us at my age have lived on\nthem,\nBut we were not all Carol Kennicotts.\nSome of us really valued a country\nsurgeon\nAnd a few of us had some idea of\nrelativity?\nFor when I wont from Main Street\nTo Yale University?\nRight into the faculty, too?\nOne of the most serious of the lovely\nwomen\nSaid to my husband, still more seri?\nously:\n\"You ji.ast not let your wife get the\nNew York habit,\"\nAll because I went over four times\nOn the 10 o'clock fast express\nTo hear the \"Nibelungenlied\"?\nThis is a relativo world. D. M.\nThe rebuke administered to Frank\nWard O'Malley by us and credited by\nhim, in this week's Satevepost, to us\nwas made substantially as quoted.\nOnly we never said \"Who the deuce\"\nin all our articulate existence.\nAccurate Enough\nSir: In a speech on Newspaper Accuracy\nbefore the C. 3. of J. Dr. Talcott Williams\ntold of how he asked his plumber what\npaper he read. The plumber answered \"The\nTrybune.\" \"Why?\" asked T. W. \"Well,\"\nsaid the plumber, \"of course,-there's a lot\nof fool stuff in it\" \"I suppose he\nmeant W. P. A.,\" T. W. added helpfully.\nDona.\nThe fight goes joyTously on. We are\ntrying to raise a fund to equip the\nproofroom with spectacles, and the\nproofroom, we hear, is soliciting con?\ntribuions toward the purchase Of a\ntypewriter for us.\n?Songs of the Stock X\nI bought me some Butterick, dear little\nButterick,\nThough 1 could never tell why.\nHut still I bought Butterick, dear little\nButterick,\nWhen it. was terribly high. Miltiades.\nIn the lirst part of \"Miss Lulu Bett\"\nthe animadversions of Dwight Herbert\nDeacon on the clock's accuracy are full\nof interest. Hardly less fascinating is\nthe following bus conversation eaves?\ndropped by L. (X:\n\"What time you got?\"\n\"Quarter t'eight.\"\n\"You wrong. It's thirteen of.\"\n\"The right time is?sixteen of.\"\n\"Listen: I set my watch September\nIG, and it's been right since\n\"This is Pennsylvania time, this\nmorning.\"\n\"This is a watch. They make\ntin- best watches. 1 got it wholesale\nthrough a friend.\"\n\"Well, a jeweler told me that my\nwas the best. It hasn't been\nregulated since I got it a year ago lust\nSeptember?no, October.\"\n\"I tell you my watch is right. I'll\nbetcha,\"\n\"I'll- take odds. What time vou go;\nnow\n\"I got five of.\"\n\"I tell you it's eight of.\"\n?They come to the Pennsylvania sta?\ntion as the hands on the big clock\nshow it to be exactly 8 o'clock.;\nCommercial Candor; or Love Dis?\nsembled\n'T see that Friskem Sinkem have\nbeen showing you some houses down in\nthe Manor,\" telephoned the Larchmont\nreal estate dealer. \"Now, Mr. L., I've\nbeen in this business thirty years and\nI've always made it a rule never to\nknock a competitor or his proposition,\n(?ood rule. Never lost nnything by it,\nbut I want to tell you, Mr. L., that\" the\nhouse they showed you down in the\nManor is built on a swamp and the\ncellur is wet six months in the year.\nIt's a nice house, but the roof leaks and\nyou'd have to put in a new heating\nplant which, the way labor is now,\nwould cost at least a thousand dollars.\nYou'd also have to put on a new roof\nthis Kail.\n\"Now, I've got two propositions that\nI think will appeal to you. One is a\ngood house and the other is new, etc.,\netc., etc., etc., etc.\" J. W. L.\nAnother neglected bard, many of\nwhoso poems appear in \"The Book of\nHumorous Verse\" is Wallace Irwin,\nwho needn't doff his bay-wreath to any?\nbody else in the versifying business.\nThe Lament of Percy Haujrhton\nGive us back the crash plays,\nThe tnckle-back, the smash plays,\nTho plunging, rippiutj dash play's.\nThe forward pass is tame.\nThe other ?lays had line plays,\nLike hurdling the line plays,\nWe need the Auld Lang Syne plays,\nTo bolster up the game\nT. F. M.\nIf Miss Zona Galt has to have a\ncollaborator, our nomination is Ridge\nly Torrence.\nEvery time we tell anybody to cheer\nup, things might be worse, we run\naway for fear we might be asked to\nspecify how. F. P. A.\nNOTHING TO GET SO ALL FIRED UPSET ABOUT\n?Copyright, 19?0. N?w York Trlban? Ino.\nA Soldier Speaks\nThose Who Bled Their Country\nWhile Others Bled for It\nTo the Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: After reading the news for the\nlast few weeks there are several things\nwhich before were inexplicable to the\nex-A. P. man that are now made\nclear.\nThe men who served in the army in\nFrance, particularly the ones who\nserved longest in the line, had been\naccustomed to misery, discomfort, pain,\nhunger and cold. A bad wound and a\nrest in the hospital were a luxury to I\nbe desired and cherished. If he got a\nClass D and was returned home as un?\nfit for military service the happiness\nof getting home, coupled with the ef?\nforts of private citizens and some few\nintelligent officials in hospitals, etc.,\nrather camouflaged the absurdity and\npompous self-importance of the aver?\nage official with whom he came in con?\ntact. The officer even smiled a little\nwhen his Sam Brown belt was pulled\nAll told, the world has never seen\na better example of close-mouthed,\ndignified acceptance of governmental\nneglect. lie accepted and gave full\nconsideration to all governmental pleas\nbased on the necessity for economy.\nHe was willing to bleed and suffer for\nhis country, hence he was not willing\nthat his country should be bled and\nsuffer for him.\nNow he is getting a lotok into the\nintricate machinery which before was\nhooded down; he sees, instead of an\nefficient machine, which, though its cost\nwent into the billions, the able, though\nlying- governmental propaganda made\nhim believe had paramount usefulness\ntoward winning the war?he sees what?\nThat, first, he will be paying taxes for\nyears on billions raised for war pur?\nposes, which were stolen by and for the\nfavored few.\nHe finds that, while he was killing\nand being killed and maimed in battle\nagainst the enemies of his country in\nFrance, at home traitors were holding\noffice in the government, using these\npositions and governmental power to\nprotect traitors; permitting a gun to\nbe held at the head of a spineless Ad?\nministration, by labor leaders, in order\nthat inefficient labor might draw pay\nfor a few hours' work which amounted\nin dollars and cents to more money\nthan he received in a month; and that\nwhile their pay checks came regularly,\nhis sometimes were four, five and six\nor more months overdue.\nWhy continue? These are but a few\nof the things he sees. lie says little,\nbut he thinks a great deal.\nMany wonder at the overwhelming\nvote against the present Administra?\ntion. I venture the assertion that this\nthinking ex-soldier and his direct in?\nfluence in family and among friends are\nworthy of consideration in this con?\nnection.\nThe outgoing Administration is, of\ncourse, no longer interested even a\nlittle in this. But I beg of the in?\ncoming that they give it due considera?\ntion, that they keep ever before them\nthe fact that he who is willing to\nbleed and has bled for his country is\ndeserving of first consideration, as\nagainst those who are willing to bleed\nand have bled their country.\nGRANT SHEPHERD.\nNew York, Nov. 23, 1920.\nBaking vs. Brewing\nTo the Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: Your correspondent, Mr. Leon\nnrd, who compares \"home baking\" with\nhome brewing\" is in error. The baker\nis allowed to make anything out of\nbread he desires. The brewer is barred\nfrom making beer, which the \"house\nbrewer\"' makes. The brewer (cereal\nleverage manufacturer) has to have a\nbrewer's license, and if he saves the\nfticofeol an ?must have an industrial\n-r\ndistiller's license. To conform with the\nlaw he must put his product through\nthree different processes in order to\nproduce a beverage which contains less\nthan Vs per cent of alcohol.\nThe home brewer makes his product\nwith one brewing and there is no tell?\ning how much alcohol it may contain.\nObviously the comparison is erroneous.\nFRED SCHWARZ.\nNew York, Nov. 20, 1920.\nThe \"Comma-Dash\" Dictators\nTo the Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: Will you kindly find space for this\nitem so that \"he who runs may read\"?\nAn advertisement is inserted asking\nfor high grade qualifications requisite\nto a position as either secretary or\nstenographer. Before many days the\napplicant is placed under the jurisdic?\ntion of a subordinate, who left school\nmany years ago and who knows little\nin -reference to ^ip-to-date pronuncia?\ntion, has limited knowledge of syntax,\nabominable punctuation, and, in fact,\nknows little of English in any of its\nbranches. In spite of all this he un?\ndertakes to call out \"Comma, dash, new\nsentence, colon, period,'* and then\n(great glory to his brilliancy) \"para?\ngraph.\" Then it is time for the old\ncat to die.\nApparently such person is not accus?\ntomed to a high grade, competent\nstenographer. And why ask for all\nthese qualifications if the dictator can?\nnot depend for these trifles upon his\nstenographer? Of course, in every case\nwhere a stenographer in with the very\nhead of the department she never hears\nall this oratory. It seems the subordi?\nnate must \"make good,\" and that is the\nway he does it.\nThis is a frequent complaint, and it\nwould be appreciated by the profession\ngenerally if this question were given\npublicity. It is an insult to one's intel?\nligence. Of course, where a beginner is\nwanted the dictator may have a reason\nfor this; even at that the beginner's\nknowledge of English may not. even b?\nso limited, either.\nLILLIAN TANNER.\nNew York, Nov. 20, 1920.\nThe Dangerous Movie\nTo the Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: In a letter by Tamas Lmne, en\ntitled \"Why Pick on the Movies?\" t\nNew York paper is scored for singlint\nout the motion picture for depictinf\ncrime, when the same thing is done ir\nnewspapers, periodicals, dramatic pro\nductions, etc.\nWhile not championing the news\npapers in any sense for their depictioi\nof crime \"which doe3 actually happen,'\nwe are surprised that Tamas Lane can\nnot. see that the scenes in motion pic\ntures are absorbed by children and ig\nnorant foreigners who can not and d?\nnot read newspapers; and dramati\nproductions are rarely witnessed b;\neither of these factions.\nThe motion picture, with its univer\nsal scope and direct contact with all th\nmasses, from the smallest child upward\nmust be especially safeguarded an\nbuilt along lines that, while furnishin;\ngood entertainment, are wholesome an\nartistic.\nIt is the flooding of tke motion pic\nture field with worthless and sugge?\ntive films that is directly responsible fo\nthe organization of the Motion Pictur\nTheatrical Association of the World an\nthe M. P. T. League for Better Pic\ntures, backed by all conscientious mem\nbers of the motion picture industry an\nprominent public organizations.\nThe motion picture business is i\nurgent need of a \"house cleaning,\" an.\nit is the duty of all *.he press, who ar\ninterested in the welfare of the peop!\nto help put this medium, which is th\ngreatest of all for good or for evil, o\nthe highest possible plane.\nJ. W. QUINN,\nPresident M. P. T. Association of the\nWorld.\nNew York, Not. 22, 1920.\nThe Diabolical Rooster\n?i\n/I Caf7 io Battle for Insomniacs\nRoused by CVon-ing\nTo the Editor of The Tribune.\nSir: Now that the election i? happily\nover we can consider some of the ques?\ntion3 of ordinary living. And an:an?\nthem the question of unnecessary noise**\nis one of the most urgent, especially fof\nsuburbanites, who have as many of therai\nto endure as the city dwellers have. Th?\nworst of these is the backyard rooster^\nand. save for those who sleep through*\nthe horrors of his near-midnight racked\nit is the most injurious to health.\nRoo;-ter crowing has the queer distinc?\ntion of being an all-or-nothing affair;\nit either does not disturb at all. or iti\ndisturbs past bearing. The people*\nwho \"love to hear them\" are without!\ncompassion for those wretched being?\nwho are driven -by them to the point on\ndangerous insomnia. The torment of tha\nvictim is augmented by the laughter or?\nthe immune, as well as by the obstinacjf\nof the owners of the beasts. And it *l\ntorment!\nTo be roused regularly at 3 o'clock hi\nthe morning, or even earlier, by\nviolent, raucous sound breakingii\nthe dead quiet of the small houi I\nto realize that if you sleep again y??4\nwill be startled awake, again, is no;\nthing which human nerves can h:\\\neasily trained to endure. Every night\nexperience increases the effect; an\nfinally the victim almost entirely Iom\nthe power to sleep either before or\nthe crowing, and the utmost he cn*t\nhope for in the whole night ia abou$\ntwo or three hours' sleep induced\nsheer exhaustion. This ruins I\nand makes him all but incapable\neither work or play. He dread I\nmere annoyance of the daylight ci I\nand other noises. He grows nervous an?\nweak, but is scorned and ridiculed unti]\nthe state of his mind equals that of bil\nbody. There is no physical depression i\nshort of severe illness, equal to that\ninsomnia; and nothing that lead*1 nie\ndirectly to melancholy.\nIt may be said that these sufferer-? af^\nin the minority; that it is nol\nwhile to consider the few who ar?\ntortured in this way. But a minority oa\nsufferers outweighs a large majority of\nthose who do not suffer. No city has th?\nright to refuse the protection of the\nlaw to any one person whose health ancf\nefficiency are seriously affected by th?\nselfishness of others.\n\"Who steals my purse steals trash.\nBut he who filches from me my [night'*)\nsleep]\nRobs me of that which not enriches him,\nAnd makes me poor indeed.\"\nChicken raisers know the ways of pre?\nventing these nuisances, by closed doorij\nproper construction of night quarterf,\netc., and they can at least be limited to\na few weeks in the course of a year.\nIf the owner believes that the cornfor?\nof a fowl means more than the worn'\nand wellbeing of a man or woman, ho\ncan at least shorten the time of hU\nvictims' torment, for most of tha\ntime the noise is tota.ly unnecessary-*\nIn any case, towns of a certain ?W\nshould pass ordinances forbidding the?\nnuisances within the city limits. T?\nis done in all places where the citi?en?\nare properly protected. In these nay*\nof difficult housing problems, to b-i\nforced to choose between moving an-i\nlosing one's health and energy is littlj\nshort of tragic. The subject deserve)\nserious consideration, and those in sy-r.?\npathy may write to\nAN OUT-OF-TOWN SUBSCRIBER\nP. O. Box 47, East Orange, N. J*\nNov. 8, 1920.\nr\nA Word for the Future\nFrom The Chicago DaHy Nevf)\nRule for shipping boards?Take\nof the millions and the billion?\nt?ke care of themselves.\n?4","height":"24939","width":"19758"}}
